| Crime & Stability      | Elevated crime rates linked to economic deprivation                               | Cycle of poverty and crime perpetuated by disinvestment ([Ejiofor, n.d.](https://redlining291756171.wordpress.com/))                                   |
| Gentrification         | Displacement of long-term residents in formerly redlined neighborhoods            | Gentrification targets historically redlined areas ([ERLC, 2018](https://erlc.com/resource-library/articles/what-you-need-to-know-about-redlining-and-gentrification/)) |

## Conclusion and Opinion

The evidence overwhelmingly indicates that redlining, though formally abolished, continues to exert a profound and multifaceted influence on American society. It has entrenched racial and economic disparities in wealth, education, health, and community stability. The structural barriers erected nearly a century ago have become self-perpetuating, creating cycles of disadvantage that are difficult to break.

Addressing these enduring effects requires comprehensive policy interventions that go beyond merely outlawing discriminatory practices. Efforts must include targeted investments in historically redlined neighborhoods, equitable school funding reforms, environmental justice initiatives, and protections against displacement due to gentrification.

In my assessment, recognizing redlining as a foundational cause of contemporary inequality is essential for crafting effective remedies. Ignoring its legacy risks perpetuating systemic racism and socio-economic stratification. Policymakers, urban planners, educators, and public health officials must collaborate to dismantle these historical inequities and promote inclusive, sustainable community development.

